Source 2: Arthur Avalon — The Serpent Power

Access status: public-domain scan / public-access OCR. Internet Archive lists a 1924 Digital Library of India scan and marks the rights as “In public domain.” It identifies the work as The Serpent Power, by Arthur Avalon, translating the Śat-Cakra-Nirūpaṇa and Pādukā-Pañcaka.

1. Source Identity

Source: The Serpent Power
Author/translator: Arthur Avalon, pen name of Sir John Woodroffe
Root texts: Śat-Cakra-Nirūpaṇa and Pādukā-Pañcaka
Tradition: Śākta Tantra / Laya Yoga / Kundalinī Yoga
Primary axis: subtle body → cakra symbolism → kuṇḍalinī ascent → Śakti-Śiva union
Best Imaginarium use: the technical architecture of the subtle-body rendering system.

Where Sivananda gives practical modern kundalini pedagogy, Avalon gives the symbolic machine: cakras, petals, bīja mantras, tattvas, deities, nāḍīs, suṣumṇā, and the metaphysics of latent power rising through the vertical human.

2. Yoga/Tantra Lineage Placement

The Serpent Power is the major English-language gateway into the cakra-kuṇḍalinī architecture of Śākta Tantra.

It should be placed as:

Not merely “energy work.”
It is a symbolic-metaphysical anatomy of consciousness.

Not merely physiology.
The cakras are not just bodily centres; they are layered world-principles, mantra-fields, deity-fields, and levels of manifestation.

Not merely mysticism.
Avalon’s presentation is technical, diagrammatic, Sanskritic, and scholastic.

Compared with Sivananda:
Sivananda = practice manual for aspirants.
Avalon = subtle-body sourcebook and symbolic grammar.

Compared with Layayoga:
Goswami expands the physiological-yogic system. Avalon preserves tantric symbolic density.

Compared with Vijñāna Bhairava:
Vijñāna Bhairava gives direct experiential entry-points; Avalon maps the inner mandala-body.

3. Structural Map
A. Long Introduction

Avalon explains Śakti, Tantra, mantra, cakras, kuṇḍalinī, yoga, and the logic of subtle embodiment.

B. Śat-Cakra-Nirūpaṇa

The six cakras are described in sequence, from mūlādhāra upward, culminating in sahasrāra.

C. Pādukā-Pañcaka

A shorter hymn-text on the guru’s feet / subtle lotus symbolism, linked to higher realization.

D. Commentary Apparatus

Avalon adds Sanskrit terms, explanatory notes, cross-references, and interpretive framing.

E. Visual Material

The plates and diagrams are crucial: they render the subtle body as symbolic architecture.

