Source 3: Shyam Sundar Goswami — Layayoga

Access status: freely hosted PDF, but likely copyrighted. Use summary-first and avoid extended quotation. The book was published in English by Inner Traditions/Simon & Schuster in 1999, and Google Books lists it as Layayoga: The Definitive Guide to the Chakras and Kundalini.

A free PDF is hosted by Theosophy World, but this should not be treated as public domain.
1. Source Identity

Source: Layayoga: The Definitive Guide to the Chakras and Kundalini
Author: Shyam Sundar Goswami
Tradition: Laya Yoga / Kundalini Yoga / subtle-body yoga
Primary axis: chakra-nāḍī physiology → concentration → dissolution → absorption into higher consciousness
Best Imaginarium use: the most systematic “subtle-body engineering” source in the sequence.

Goswami’s importance is that he treats chakras and nāḍīs not as vague symbolic tropes but as a rigorous yogic anatomy of transformation.

2. Yoga/Tantra Lineage Placement

Layayoga sits between Haṭha Yoga, Kundalini Yoga, and Rāja Yoga. The Goswami Yoga Institute describes Layayoga as a chakra science, also called Kundalini Yoga, occupying a middle position between Haṭha and Rāja Yoga.

Compared with the other sources:

Sivananda: practical, devotional, synthetic pedagogy.
Goswami: technical, systematic, anatomical-subtle, chakra-by-chakra.

The Serpent Power: tantric symbolic architecture.
Goswami: yogic physiology and meditative mechanics.

Vijñāna Bhairava: direct recognition through perception.
Goswami: gradual internalization through subtle centres.

Mahānirvāṇa Tantra: Śākta ritual theology.
Goswami: interior yogic dissolution.

Vajrayāna tantras: deity, mandala, initiation, secrecy.
Goswami: subtle-body concentration and absorption.

3. Structural Map
A. Foundations of Laya

Defines laya as dissolution, absorption, and retraction of mental-energy processes into deeper consciousness.

B. Subtle Body Framework

Maps chakras, nāḍīs, kuṇḍalinī, prāṇa, mantra, and concentration.

C. Chakra-by-Chakra System

Each centre is treated as a field with structure, symbolism, function, and meditative significance.

D. Descent / Spiritualization

Unlike common upward-only kundalini models, some descriptions of Layayoga emphasize starting from sahasrāra and spiritualizing the centres downward.

E. Integration

The system joins concentration, mantra, body, energy, symbol, and consciousness into a single yogic method.

