Source 16: Patañjali — Yoga Sūtras / Pātañjalayogaśāstra

Access status: public-domain translations/scans available. Internet Archive hosts James Haughton Woods’ 1914 Yoga-System of Patañjali and marks it “In Public Domain.” Sacred Texts also hosts Charles Johnston’s 1912 translation.

1. Source Identity

Source: Yoga Sūtras of Patañjali
Commentarial frame: traditionally read with the Yoga Bhāṣya
Tradition: Classical Yoga / Sāṃkhya-Yoga
Primary axis: citta-vṛtti-nirodha → samādhi → discriminative knowledge → kaivalya
Best Imaginarium use: the “mind-rendering control text”: how perception, identity, memory, affliction, and liberation depend on the stilling and clarification of the mind-field.

2. Yoga/Tantra Lineage Placement

This is not a tantra text in the same sense as Vijñāna Bhairava, Mahānirvāṇa, Hevajra, or Kālacakra. It is the classical yogic foundation that later yoga/tantra systems repeatedly inherit, adapt, or react against.

Compared with prior sources:

Sivananda: modern kundalinī pedagogy.
Yoga Sūtras: classical mental discipline and samādhi theory.

The Serpent Power / Layayoga: subtle-body architecture and energetic dissolution.
Yoga Sūtras: mind-field analysis, afflictions, concentration, and kaivalya.

Vijñāna Bhairava: direct recognition through gaps, shock, breath, void, sensation.
Yoga Sūtras: systematic restraint of mental fluctuations.

Haṭha sources: body-breath technologies.
Yoga Sūtras: why body-breath work matters: it stabilizes the mind for samādhi.

3. Structural Map
A. Samādhi Pāda

Defines yoga as cessation/restriction of mental fluctuations and maps concentration, practice, dispassion, and samādhi.

B. Sādhana Pāda

Explains practice, afflictions, karma, suffering, and the eight limbs.

C. Vibhūti Pāda

Describes dhāraṇā, dhyāna, samādhi, saṃyama, and extraordinary capacities as by-products.

D. Kaivalya Pāda

Clarifies liberation, mind, latent impressions, guṇas, puruṣa, and final isolation/freedom.

